00:02:56.020 --> 00:02:58.070
Again, it's an honor
to join you here

00:02:58.070 --> 00:03:01.490
to talk about my book, "50
Ways to Excel in Your First Job

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:03.100
and in Life."

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:05.280
This is critical to me
because my passion really

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:06.790
is supporting
young professionals

00:03:06.790 --> 00:03:10.160
in doing exceptional
things in their career,

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:14.016
making them aware of the
choices that they have in life.

00:03:14.016 --> 00:03:16.640
And the reason why I wrote this
book is because frankly, what I

00:03:16.640 --> 00:03:18.056
share in this book
are things that

00:03:18.056 --> 00:03:20.200
have made a big
difference in my life.

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:22.150
And I would not be here
talking to you today

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:25.440
without some of those key
lessons I share in that book.

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:27.760
You see, as I traveled
across the country, those 15,

00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:30.240
those 20,000 miles
a month, what I

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:32.100
see are a lot of
young professionals

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:35.750
and college students
who, on paper, on paper,

00:03:35.750 --> 00:03:37.860
everything looks right.

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:41.450
But as we all know, on paper
only tells part of the story.

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:43.780
Maybe you go to the
right university.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:46.570
Maybe you have the right
grade point average.

00:03:46.570 --> 00:03:48.650
Maybe you're part of
the right organizations.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:50.700
Maybe you've had the
right internships.

00:03:50.700 --> 00:03:52.340
But what I've seen
firsthand are so

00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:54.040
many young professionals
who are kind of

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:56.510
like a high-powered jet.

00:03:56.510 --> 00:03:59.760
They're barreling down
the runway at full speed.

00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:03.070
But for some reason,
they can't take off.

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:06.120
They're struggling to
take off in their career.

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:08.060
And the research
actually backs this up.

00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:09.980
We can look at some
research from Gallup

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:12.650
way back in 2015,
last year, that

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:15.940
said employers are finding that
many college graduates are not

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:18.570
prepared with the
skills that they need

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:20.902
to succeed in the workforce.

00:04:20.902 --> 00:04:22.860
Now, the skills they're
talking about something

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:23.850
called soft skills.

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:25.060
That's about leadership.

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:26.150
That's communication.

00:04:26.150 --> 00:04:28.930
That's collaboration,
emotional intelligence.

00:04:28.930 --> 00:04:31.770
They say young professionals
like yourself aren't prepared

00:04:31.770 --> 00:04:33.344
with creative thinking.

00:04:33.344 --> 00:04:35.260
And they say young
professionals like yourself

00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:39.550
aren't ready with good
problem-solving skills.

00:04:39.550 --> 00:04:42.237
Now, on the flipside,
Deloitte did a study.

00:04:42.237 --> 00:04:44.320
And that said that young
professionals and college

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:46.620
students like
yourselves don't think

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:49.540
that their skill sets,
their academic education,

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:52.350
is valued by employers.

00:04:52.350 --> 00:04:54.180
So obviously, we have a divide.

00:04:54.180 --> 00:04:56.270
And the stakes are
extremely high, right?

00:04:56.270 --> 00:05:00.670
Because a corporation, when
they hire you to work with them,

00:05:00.670 --> 00:05:04.340
they spend a lot of money
to find you, to develop you,

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:06.100
to groom you to succeed.

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.720
And all of you who are getting
your education right now,

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:11.960
you've spent a lot of
money on your education,

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:13.700
getting ready to
succeed in your life.

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:16.631
So you want a return
on that investment.

00:05:16.631 --> 00:05:18.130
So what I hope to
share in this book

00:05:18.130 --> 00:05:21.470
is what can bridge that divide.

00:05:21.470 --> 00:05:22.900
You know, before
I go any further,

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:24.490
I think it's really important
to share a little bit more

00:05:24.490 --> 00:05:27.100
about my background so you can
tell where I'm coming from,

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:28.740
where I share this information.

00:05:28.740 --> 00:05:30.694
So if you happen to do
a Google search on me,

00:05:30.694 --> 00:05:33.360
you'll find that I worked in the
television industry in New York

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:37.140
City for over 10 years as a
reporter, as a correspondent,

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:39.190
as a host with NBC.

00:05:39.190 --> 00:05:41.844
I've interviewed top CEOs,
executives, and entrepreneurs,

00:05:41.844 --> 00:05:43.260
the men and the
women that you see

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:46.860
on the covers of "Fast
Company" and "Inc. Magazine."

00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:49.660
With PBS, on "The NewsHour"
and the [INAUDIBLE] news,

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:52.190
I've covered serious topics
like international trade,

00:05:52.190 --> 00:05:55.800
the economy, education,
the Supreme Court.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:56.300
With "E!

00:05:56.300 --> 00:06:00.640
News Live," I've interviewed
popstars like Aaron Carter.

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:04.140
With the BET networks, I've
created documentary series.

00:06:04.140 --> 00:06:06.550
My writing can be read
in a variety of outlets

00:06:06.550 --> 00:06:09.412
like "Inc. Magazine"
and entrepreneur.com.

00:06:09.412 --> 00:06:12.850
I lead the higher education
team at International Personal

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:15.420
Branding Platform about me.

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:18.000
And a little-known fact
that was mentioned briefly

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.760
in my introduction is that
I began my career co-hosting

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:26.100
shows on a television network
called Nickelodeon, way

00:06:26.100 --> 00:06:29.050
back in 2002 to 2004 or 2005.

00:06:29.050 --> 00:06:30.980
If you're confused, I'm
the handsome brother

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:34.010
in the corner with
the dreadlocks.

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:36.140
This was a long time ago
when I began my career.

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:37.515
So if you've ever
asked yourself,

00:06:37.515 --> 00:06:40.770
you know, I wonder whatever
happens to former Nickelodeon

00:06:40.770 --> 00:06:41.670
hosts.

00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:42.170
What's up?

00:06:42.170 --> 00:06:43.336
How's everybody doing today?

00:06:43.336 --> 00:06:45.460
Good to see you.

00:06:45.460 --> 00:06:47.650
Now, look, I don't
show these credentials,

00:06:47.650 --> 00:06:49.490
I don't show these
networks to you

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:52.610
and all this fun stuff to
brag or to boast, by no means.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:58.020
Because these are my credits,
my Google search today.

00:06:58.020 --> 00:07:01.980
But 15 years ago, if you
did that exact same search,

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:04.960
this is what you would find.

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:07.141
You wouldn't find anything.

00:07:07.141 --> 00:07:08.640
Maybe for many of
you, this is where

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:10.610
you are right now
as you are beginning

00:07:10.610 --> 00:07:14.010
your career, this blank
slate, this blank canvas.

00:07:14.010 --> 00:07:17.165
You see, I'm from a
small town in Michigan.

00:07:17.165 --> 00:07:18.540
I'm from one of
those small towns

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:22.120
where people do not leave.

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:24.530
I am from a family
that experienced

00:07:24.530 --> 00:07:26.590
a lot of instability.

00:07:26.590 --> 00:07:30.300
Before I graduated from high
school, I moved over 15 times,

00:07:30.300 --> 00:07:34.180
over 15 times in
my small hometown.

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:40.261
Between my mother and father are
a total of like six divorces.

00:07:40.261 --> 00:07:41.760
I also know what
it's like firsthand

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:43.745
to live in a
shelter for battered

00:07:43.745 --> 00:07:46.640
and abused women and children.

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:48.330
I'm a first generation
college student,

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:50.150
the first person my
family to go to college

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:53.600
and be able to earn a degree.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:55.600
Now, I don't share
any of this with you

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:59.841
to elicit any
sympathy, by no means.

00:07:59.841 --> 00:08:02.090
I only know if I had to share
with you, for many years

00:08:02.090 --> 00:08:06.530
I was ashamed of it, and
I was embarrassed by it.

00:08:06.530 --> 00:08:09.440
But oddly enough, I found
that those things right there

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:12.310
are many of the reasons why I'm
standing here with you today.

00:08:12.310 --> 00:08:14.960
It built up a certain amount
of grit that a lot of people

00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:16.041
are talking about today.

00:08:16.041 --> 00:08:18.040
There's a great book out
right now called "Grit"

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:19.890
by Angela Duckworth.

00:08:19.890 --> 00:08:22.460
Let's build up that grit, that
perseverance, that resilience,

00:08:22.460 --> 00:08:25.456
that character to move forward
through challenging times.

00:08:25.456 --> 00:08:27.330
Now, many of you, there's
something about you

00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:31.621
that's unique that someone would
never find in a Google search.

00:08:31.621 --> 00:08:33.120
And I want you to
know that whatever

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:35.130
that is that people
may not know right now,

00:08:35.130 --> 00:08:38.860
use that to your advantage,
not your disadvantage.

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:42.434
Own that, as opposed
to hide that.

00:08:42.434 --> 00:08:44.090
And you have a blank
canvas right now.

00:08:44.090 --> 00:08:45.950
As you begin this summer
and you begin your career,

00:08:45.950 --> 00:08:47.491
you have a blank
canvas, if you will,

00:08:47.491 --> 00:08:49.460
to paint and to create
and to scope what

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:51.432
you most want in your life.

00:08:51.432 --> 00:08:53.140
And I believe the
three things that we'll

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:55.681
get into today that will allow
you to do that are these three

00:08:55.681 --> 00:09:00.420
topics right here, that is being
willing to turn up the volume,

00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:03.990
being willing to find the
edge, and being willing to do

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:05.540
something that seems obvious.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:08.270
But for some reason, not a lot
of people do that, that is,

00:09:08.270 --> 00:09:11.679
find people who make you better.

00:09:11.679 --> 00:09:13.220
And if there's a
thesis of everything

00:09:13.220 --> 00:09:15.030
that I do of my work,
it's this right here.

00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:20.100
That is, being willing to
be the CEO of your career.

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:23.350
I've had the opportunity over
my life to interview and profile

00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:26.120
extremely talented
CEOs, entrepreneurs,

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:28.544
you name it, who've built
billion-dollar companies.

00:09:28.544 --> 00:09:30.960
And one thing I've noticed in
these men and women is this,

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:33.830
is that they take
full accountability

00:09:33.830 --> 00:09:36.970
and responsibility
for their experience.

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:38.690
They're willing
to have an agenda.

00:09:38.690 --> 00:09:40.170
They're willing to have goals.

00:09:40.170 --> 00:09:43.752
They're willing to be
proactive versus reactive.

00:09:43.752 --> 00:09:46.210
A lot of employees come and
they wait for things to happen.

00:09:46.210 --> 00:09:48.460
I'm inviting all of you over
the course of this summer

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:51.900
to be proactive and
make things happen.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:53.980
Yes, Google's going to do
amazing things for you.

00:09:53.980 --> 00:09:56.580
The question begs, what
can you do for yourself

00:09:56.580 --> 00:09:59.842
during this time
that you are here?

00:09:59.842 --> 00:10:02.990
So let's get into this
with turning up the volume.

00:10:02.990 --> 00:10:05.030
Many years ago, I
started my career.

00:10:05.030 --> 00:10:08.260
I worked briefly as a local
news reporter for a really small

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:09.096
television station.

00:10:09.096 --> 00:10:12.260
Now, I remember walking into
my news station one day.

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:14.690
And my news director
happened to be sitting there.

00:10:14.690 --> 00:10:17.580
And he was looking at a
reels that reporters had sent

00:10:17.580 --> 00:10:19.562
in from all across the country.

00:10:19.562 --> 00:10:21.020
These are men and
women that wanted

00:10:21.020 --> 00:10:23.228
to work for the television
station that I worked for.

00:10:23.228 --> 00:10:25.550
They wanted to replace me.

00:10:25.550 --> 00:10:26.590
So he saw me.

00:10:26.590 --> 00:10:30.002
And he called me into the office
to watch these reels with him.

00:10:30.002 --> 00:10:32.210
And after a few moments of
watching some of the reels

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:35.110
with him, I had to
ask him to stop.

00:10:35.110 --> 00:10:36.947
And we pushed pause.

00:10:36.947 --> 00:10:39.280
Because what I noticed, as
we were watching these reels,

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:43.270
was that the volume was
turned down on the television.

00:10:43.270 --> 00:10:45.730
Now, as we all know,
television it's an audio,

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:47.950
it's a visual medium.

00:10:47.950 --> 00:10:50.920
So I said, boss, how can
you hire this young man

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:52.640
or hire this young
woman if you can't

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:54.760
hear what they are saying.

00:10:54.760 --> 00:10:55.550
He looked at me.

00:10:55.550 --> 00:10:56.690
He smiled.

00:10:56.690 --> 00:11:00.220
It was as if he had been
anticipating this question.

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:03.780
And he said, Antonio,
I want to see if I

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:07.525
want to turn the volume up.

00:11:07.525 --> 00:11:11.222
I want to see if I want
to turn the volume up.

00:11:11.222 --> 00:11:13.430
Think about those moments
in life you've been at home

00:11:13.430 --> 00:11:15.600
and five million different
things are going on.

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:16.805
The radio is blasting.

00:11:16.805 --> 00:11:17.860
You're on social media.

00:11:17.860 --> 00:11:18.490
You're cooking.

00:11:18.490 --> 00:11:19.210
You're doing dishes.

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:20.418
You're having a conversation.

00:11:20.418 --> 00:11:22.100
But something happens
to be happening

00:11:22.100 --> 00:11:24.680
on the television that
grabs your attention

00:11:24.680 --> 00:11:27.900
and you have to find that remote
control to turn up the volume

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:29.620
to see what's being said.

00:11:29.620 --> 00:11:32.860
Or maybe you've been at
a party or a gathering.

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:35.800
And you're having a conversation
with her right here.

00:11:35.800 --> 00:11:36.800
And she's cool, right?

