Right?

00:11:37.300 --> 00:11:38.310
We're having a
good conversation.

00:11:38.310 --> 00:11:38.980
OK.

00:11:38.980 --> 00:11:41.560
But at some point during
that party, that gathering,

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:44.790
you notice another conversation
happening over here

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:46.490
that you want to turn
the volume up on.

00:11:46.490 --> 00:11:47.740
Like, hey, I'll see you later.

00:11:47.740 --> 00:11:49.600
Deuces.

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:51.730
Well, believe it or
not, every single day

00:11:51.730 --> 00:11:53.563
over the course of your
life-- and they say,

00:11:53.563 --> 00:11:55.030
don't judge a book by its cover.

00:11:55.030 --> 00:11:55.900
But let's be real.

00:11:55.900 --> 00:11:58.220
Keep it 100, as they say.

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:00.309
People do.

00:12:00.309 --> 00:12:01.850
People are determining
whether or not

00:12:01.850 --> 00:12:04.450
they want to turn
the volume up on you

00:12:04.450 --> 00:12:07.330
or press mute in your career.

00:12:07.330 --> 00:12:11.730
They are doing that based
on what time you show up.

00:12:11.730 --> 00:12:16.100
They are doing that based
on how you present yourself.

00:12:16.100 --> 00:12:20.042
They are doing that based on
your body language and energy.

00:12:20.042 --> 00:12:21.500
They are determining
whether or not

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:23.620
they want to turn the
volume up on you based

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:27.835
on what shows up with you
when you come into a room.

00:12:27.835 --> 00:12:29.210
Have you ever been
to a gathering

00:12:29.210 --> 00:12:32.870
or a party and the door opens
and you look over and it's Tim?

00:12:32.870 --> 00:12:35.390
And you're like oh, Tim.

00:12:35.390 --> 00:12:38.550
And you know the party
is about to get worse?

00:12:38.550 --> 00:12:41.890
You know that person that makes
the party-- you're like, oh.

00:12:41.890 --> 00:12:45.160
And there have been other times,
you're at this same party.

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:46.260
You hear the door open.

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:47.152
You look.

00:12:47.152 --> 00:12:47.860
And it's Deborah.

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:50.050
And you're like,
oh, Deborah's here.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:53.890
And you know the party's
about to get better.

00:12:53.890 --> 00:12:56.820
Do people want to turn
the volume up on you

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:59.240
or turn it down and press mute?

00:12:59.240 --> 00:13:02.480
In this day and age, we hear
a lot about personal brand

00:13:02.480 --> 00:13:05.920
and how important it is for you
to develop your personal brand.

00:13:05.920 --> 00:13:07.710
Well, the best
definition that I've

00:13:07.710 --> 00:13:10.360
heard that relates to
personal branding is this.

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:13.900
Your personal brand is
what people say about you

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:17.180
when you are not around.

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:18.620
That's a simple way to put it.

00:13:18.620 --> 00:13:20.790
I don't care if it's
online or in person.

00:13:20.790 --> 00:13:23.390
Your personal brand is
what people say about you

00:13:23.390 --> 00:13:24.960
when you are not around.

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:28.520
What I invite all of you to
do after you leave here today

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:32.500
is open up a Google
Chrome browser,

00:13:32.500 --> 00:13:35.550
and then open up
a private window,

00:13:35.550 --> 00:13:39.690
and then Google your name and
see what those results are.

00:13:39.690 --> 00:13:40.680
Because guess what?

00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:42.140
You're not around when
somebody does that.

00:13:42.140 --> 00:13:42.848
You meet someone.

00:13:42.848 --> 00:13:43.900
What do you do?

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:45.740
You Google their name.

00:13:45.740 --> 00:13:47.940
It's so funny when I do
this exercise with people.

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:49.250
They'll go to that
private browser.

00:13:49.250 --> 00:13:51.250
Don't go to a regular
browser because you Google

00:13:51.250 --> 00:13:52.930
yourself all the time anyways.

00:13:52.930 --> 00:13:54.260
But go to the private browser.

00:13:54.260 --> 00:13:54.968
Google your name.

00:13:54.968 --> 00:13:59.530
And I see people do things
like, that's not me.

00:13:59.530 --> 00:14:01.560
Other people look
at that and say,

00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:04.080
that's not a
flattering photo of me.

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:06.630
People look at
that and say, yeah,

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:09.180
that last Instagram post isn't
really what I'm all about.

00:14:09.180 --> 00:14:11.120
But it is me.

00:14:11.120 --> 00:14:13.120
Your personal brand is
what people say about you

00:14:13.120 --> 00:14:14.790
when you're not around.

00:14:14.790 --> 00:14:19.030
Now, to continue on this theme
of turning up the volume,

00:14:19.030 --> 00:14:21.330
do we have any country
music fans in the room?

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:23.360
Raise your hand.

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:24.030
Six people.

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:26.140
OK, well, we'll talk
about hip-hop instead.

00:14:26.140 --> 00:14:28.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:28.430 --> 00:14:29.430
I'm a big hip-hop fan.

00:14:29.430 --> 00:14:34.680
And way back in 2001, I went to
a rap concert in New York City,

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:36.039
in Irving Plaza.

00:14:36.039 --> 00:14:37.830
I went to go see one
of my favorite artists

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:40.740
at the time, this guy by
the name of Talib Kweli.

00:14:40.740 --> 00:14:43.160
And he is still one of
my favorite artists.

00:14:43.160 --> 00:14:44.750
I remember getting
to the venue early,

00:14:44.750 --> 00:14:46.290
right when the doors opened.

00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:48.200
And as I was walking
in, I heard someone

00:14:48.200 --> 00:14:50.300
say from the loudspeakers,
ladies and gentlemen,

00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:53.200
it's time for our opening act.

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:54.617
You don't know who
this person is.

00:14:54.617 --> 00:14:56.158
You probably haven't
heard the music.

00:14:56.158 --> 00:14:57.490
But they're extremely talented.

00:14:57.490 --> 00:14:59.780
Please give your love,
please give your attention,

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:02.490
please give your energy
to our opening act.

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:06.170
And this opening act came
out and started performing.

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:08.620
Now, I invite all of you
to think about those times

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:11.610
that you've been to a concert
and the opening act comes out

00:15:11.610 --> 00:15:13.790
and you are not
familiar with them,

00:15:13.790 --> 00:15:16.350
and you are not familiar
with their music.

00:15:16.350 --> 00:15:18.066
What do you do?

00:15:18.066 --> 00:15:21.260
Well, people I know, typically,
they'll pull out their phone.

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:22.700
They'll have a conversation.

00:15:22.700 --> 00:15:23.910
They'll grab some beverages.

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:25.690
They'll do anything
but pay attention

00:15:25.690 --> 00:15:27.307
to the person on stage.

00:15:27.307 --> 00:15:28.890
It's not because
they're not talented.

00:15:28.890 --> 00:15:30.389
It's not because
they're not gifted.

00:15:30.389 --> 00:15:32.320
It's just that they
don't have any context.

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:35.520
And look, in 2001,
there was no SoundCloud.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:37.810
So you weren't researching
this in advance.

00:15:37.810 --> 00:15:40.880
But interestingly enough,
after that opening act started

00:15:40.880 --> 00:15:45.350
performing, they made me and
a few others in that venue

00:15:45.350 --> 00:15:48.794
want to turn the volume up.

00:15:48.794 --> 00:15:51.210
And the reason why they made
me want to turn the volume up

00:15:51.210 --> 00:15:54.290
is because, even though pretty
much no one-- and I mean

00:15:54.290 --> 00:15:56.440
no one-- was paying
attention to them,

00:15:56.440 --> 00:16:00.610
they still were giving
absolutely everything.

00:16:00.610 --> 00:16:02.150
It was as if this
opening act was

00:16:02.150 --> 00:16:05.222
performing to a sold-out
arena, while no one was

00:16:05.222 --> 00:16:05.930
paying attention.

00:16:05.930 --> 00:16:08.240
It was as if the
pope this opening act

00:16:08.240 --> 00:16:11.490
was a multi-platinum Grammy
Award winning artist.

00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:16.650
It was as if this opening
act was already performing

00:16:16.650 --> 00:16:18.500
at the MTV Music Awards.

00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:21.180
While no one was
paying attention,

00:16:21.180 --> 00:16:25.706
they were giving
absolutely everything.

00:16:25.706 --> 00:16:27.580
The question I have for
everyone in this room

00:16:27.580 --> 00:16:31.244
is, what do you do when no
one is paying attention?

00:16:31.244 --> 00:16:33.410
Think about those times
you've been in the classroom

00:16:33.410 --> 00:16:35.201
or you've been involved
in a group project,

00:16:35.201 --> 00:16:38.280
and you know there is that one
person, because there's always

00:16:38.280 --> 00:16:41.860
that one person that will do
all the work in that group.

00:16:41.860 --> 00:16:43.450
You know that person?

00:16:43.450 --> 00:16:47.110
Do you let them do all the
work just because they will?

00:16:47.110 --> 00:16:49.110
Or maybe you've been
really committed to getting

00:16:49.110 --> 00:16:51.930
in better shape when you meet a
friend of yours a couple times

00:16:51.930 --> 00:16:54.990
a week at 6:00 AM
to go to the gym.

00:16:54.990 --> 00:16:57.740
But the night before, you
get a text message that says,

00:16:57.740 --> 00:17:00.310
dude, not going to
be able to make it.

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:03.700
Do you still go to the gym
even though that person is not

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:05.540
going to be there?

00:17:05.540 --> 00:17:09.210
Or maybe even really cognizant
of focusing on your health

00:17:09.210 --> 00:17:11.520
and wellness and not
eating processed foods,

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:12.450
but it's late night.

00:17:12.450 --> 00:17:13.119
You're tired.

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:15.077
The last thing you want
to do when you get home

00:17:15.077 --> 00:17:15.950
is cook something.

00:17:15.950 --> 00:17:19.359
And you happen to pass by
a fast food restaurant.

00:17:19.359 --> 00:17:22.040
Do you still pull in
when no one is watching?

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:24.180
What do you do when
no one pays attention?

00:17:24.180 --> 00:17:25.569
I'm a firm believer
that what you

00:17:25.569 --> 00:17:27.460
do when no one is
paying attention

00:17:27.460 --> 00:17:30.720
will deliver the results
you do or do not want.

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:34.780
Well, getting back to that
concert way back in 2001,

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:36.560
that person on stage
really impressed me.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:38.390
But time came and went.

00:17:38.390 --> 00:17:42.732
But I remember in 2004,
three years later-- 2004,

00:17:42.732 --> 00:17:44.690
three years later, I
remember hearing some buzz

00:17:44.690 --> 00:17:47.480
about some new
artist on the scene.

00:17:47.480 --> 00:17:49.640
Some new album was
dropped the everyone was

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:51.790
raving about and talking about.

00:17:51.790 --> 00:17:54.480
So I keep all the ticket
stubs for the concerts

00:17:54.480 --> 00:17:56.220
and the sporting
events that I go to.

00:17:56.220 --> 00:17:58.390
And I went and grabbed
that ticket stub

00:17:58.390 --> 00:18:01.010
and I cross-referenced
it with that album

00:18:01.010 --> 00:18:02.670
and all those articles.

00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:04.660
And I found out
that that person who

00:18:04.660 --> 00:18:09.140
was giving absolutely everything
when no one was watching

00:18:09.140 --> 00:18:16.204
three years earlier was someone
by the name of Kanye West.

00:18:16.204 --> 00:18:18.370
Now, it goes without saying
that Kanye West believes

00:18:18.370 --> 00:18:19.292
in Kanye West.

00:18:19.292 --> 00:18:20.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:20.650 --> 00:18:23.010
Is that fair to say?

00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:25.150
The question is if
Kanye West did not

00:18:25.150 --> 00:18:29.180
believe in Kanye West three
years earlier, who would have?

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:31.730
People give this man a lot of
ridicule and a lot of flack

00:18:31.730 --> 00:18:34.380
for his social media
rants and if you

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:37.320
want to call them,
diatribes and his opinions.

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:39.930
But I don't look at
this man the same way

00:18:39.930 --> 00:18:44.160
because for three years,
before anyone knew his name,

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:46.502
he was giving absolutely
everything while no one was

00:18:46.502 --> 00:18:47.210
paying attention.

00:18:47.210 --> 00:18:48.990
In many ways, I feel
like he's earned it.

00:18:48.990 --> 00:18:52.419
He can say whatever
he wants to say.

00:18:52.419 --> 00:18:54.960
His success didn't come three
months later, six months later,

00:18:54.960 --> 00:18:56.320
one year later, two years later.

00:18:56.320 --> 00:18:59.616
No, three years later,
the album came out.

00:18:59.616 --> 00:19:00.990
While no one was
watching, he was

00:19:00.990 --> 00:19:02.210
giving absolutely everything.

00:19:02.210 --> 00:19:06.657
What do you do when
no one is watching?

00:19:06.657 --> 00:19:08.740
What this gets across for
me this whole notion of,

00:19:08.740 --> 00:19:11.770
you don't climb a
mountain by accident

00:19:11.770 --> 00:19:13.910
over the course of your career.

00:19:13.910 --> 00:19:15.851
I talk to a lot of
young professionals.

00:19:15.851 --> 00:19:17.850
And I do a lot of consulting
with organizations.

00:19:17.850 --> 00:19:19.920
And a similar refrain
is that people

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:21.560
want more responsibility.

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:23.070
They want the bigger projects.

00:19:23.070 --> 00:19:25.010
They want the bigger
titles, you name it.

00:19:25.010 --> 00:19:27.330
But you don't climb a
mountain by accident.

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:30.470
If somehow, I could
miraculously airlift you

00:19:30.470 --> 00:19:34.210
to the top of Mount Kilimanjaro
or to the top of, let's say,

00:19:34.210 --> 00:19:37.120
Mount Everest, which is
nearly 30,000 feet altitude,

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:39.850
what would happen
when you got out?

00:19:39.850 --> 00:19:42.190
You would take in
this amazing view.

00:19:42.190 --> 00:19:45.560
And you would probably
pass out afterwards.

00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:47.960
And the reason why
is because your lungs

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:51.960
have not earned being
at that altitude.

00:19:51.960 --> 00:19:54.290
You have not done the work
when no one is watching.

00:19:54.290 --> 00:19:57.140
It's no wonder when we think
about reality television--

00:19:57.140 --> 00:20:00.540
I enjoy the reality television
competitions like anyone else.

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:03.530
But there's no wonder that
one or two years after someone

00:20:03.530 --> 00:20:05.790
wins that television
competition,

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:09.906
we no longer hear that
man or woman's name.

00:20:09.906 --> 00:20:11.780
It's not because, again,
they're not talented

00:20:11.780 --> 00:20:13.010
or they're not gifted.

00:20:13.010 --> 00:20:15.430
It's because they
haven't done the work

00:20:15.430 --> 00:20:16.940
when no one was watching.

00:20:16.940 --> 00:20:19.190
It was handed to
them prematurely.

00:20:19.190 --> 00:20:22.030
Has anyone in this room ever--
has anybody here ever driven

00:20:22.030 --> 00:20:24.330
a stick-shift before?

00:20:24.330 --> 00:20:26.140
OK, what happens
if you try to start

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:29.574
a stick-shift in fifth gear?

00:20:29.574 --> 00:20:30.490
You're going to stall.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:32.679
Yeah, you're not going
to have a lot of luck.

00:20:32.679 --> 00:20:34.720
What I see happening with
people in their careers

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:38.530
is they're trying to get
to fifth gear right away.

00:20:38.530 --> 00:20:40.070
The opportunity
that all of us have

00:20:40.070 --> 00:20:43.790
is to be willing to earn first
gear, to earn second gear,

00:20:43.790 --> 00:20:46.960
to earn third year, and
even learn to enjoy those

00:20:46.960 --> 00:20:52.504
stalls because that right there
is where the magic happens.

00:20:52.504 --> 00:20:54.670
What I want to get across
to you is this right here,

00:20:54.670 --> 00:20:58.220
that ideas are useless.

00:20:58.220 --> 00:21:01.270
Ideas are useless until you
breathe some type of life

00:21:01.270 --> 00:21:01.960
into them.

00:21:01.960 --> 00:21:04.740
Right now, on some
of your hard drives

00:21:04.740 --> 00:21:07.940
are some of the best ideas
ever that you have never

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:09.525
taken action on.

00:21:09.525 --> 00:21:11.400
Right now, somewhere in
one of your notebooks

00:21:11.400 --> 00:21:12.940
that's packed away
in a file cabinet,

00:21:12.940 --> 00:21:15.356
or maybe in your notebook right
in front of you right now,

00:21:15.356 --> 00:21:17.440
are amazing ideas
that for some reason,

00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:19.406
you have yet to take action on.

00:21:19.406 --> 00:21:20.780
Right now, some
of the best ideas

00:21:20.780 --> 00:21:24.150
are happening over brunch
conversations with mimosas.

00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:25.780
But after that second
mimosa, the idea

00:21:25.780 --> 00:21:27.660
goes out of the window.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:30.670
Ideas are useless unless
you breathe life into them.

00:21:30.670 --> 00:21:32.170
When I started off
in Nickelodeon,

00:21:32.170 --> 00:21:36.170
I didn't start off
as a television host.

00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:38.830
I actually started off working
on a show as a production

00:21:38.830 --> 00:21:39.572
assistant.

00:21:39.572 --> 00:21:41.780
Now, if you know anything
about working in television

00:21:41.780 --> 00:21:43.363
and working as a
production assistant,

00:21:43.363 --> 00:21:46.530
you know that it is not a sexy--
it is not a glamorous job.

00:21:46.530 --> 00:21:47.490
You're making coffee.

00:21:47.490 --> 00:21:48.610
You're making photocopies.

00:21:48.610 --> 00:21:50.040
You're holding cue cards.

00:21:50.040 --> 00:21:52.330
You're carrying
equipment around.

00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:55.160
But one of my goals
was to be a writer.

00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:58.700
So after all my responsibilities
were complete, I would write.

00:21:58.700 --> 00:22:00.200
I took writing classes.

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:01.990
I studied great writers.

00:22:01.990 --> 00:22:04.990
And slowly but surely,
my writing improved.

00:22:04.990 --> 00:22:06.990
And after a while, I
built up enough confidence

00:22:06.990 --> 00:22:09.230
to go to the head writer
of the television show

00:22:09.230 --> 00:22:11.800
that I worked on to ask him
if he'd be willing to give me

00:22:11.800 --> 00:22:13.750
feedback on my scripts.

00:22:13.750 --> 00:22:15.906
And he said absolutely.

00:22:15.906 --> 00:22:17.280
And I learned
another key lesson.

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:23.150
That is nine times out of 10,
people are willing to help you.

00:22:23.150 --> 00:22:27.080
But it is your responsibility
to ask for that help.

